          <span class="eyebrow">Route planner</span>
          <h1>Which Claw should I choose?</h1>
          <p class="lede">If you’re standing on the boardwalk wondering where to begin, this is the short answer page. Pick the project that matches your appetite, hardware, risk tolerance, and patience for complexity.</p>
        </div>
        <aside class="note-card">
          <h3>Fast read</h3>
          <p>OpenClaw is the broad canonical pier. NanoClaw is the cautious tinkerer's harbor. PicoClaw is the tiny-hardware route. NemoClaw is the safety-forward experiment.</p>
        </aside>
      </div>

      <div class="summary">
        <strong>Destination card:</strong> this page is one stop on the rack — use it when you already know the kind of question you're asking, and hop back to the front page when you want the broader map again.
      </div>

      <div class="grid">
        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Choose OpenClaw</span>
          <h2>If you want the main ecosystem</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> people who want the canonical docs, biggest project surface, and strongest ecosystem gravity.</li>
            <li><strong>Choose it if:</strong> you want the main reference point and don’t mind more moving parts.</li>
            <li><strong>Watch for:</strong> broader complexity and a need for more deliberate setup hygiene.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Choose NanoClaw</span>
          <h2>If you want clarity and containment</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> cautious tinkerers, security-minded users, and people who like readable code.</li>
            <li><strong>Choose it if:</strong> you want a smaller mental model and container-first habits.</li>
            <li><strong>Watch for:</strong> a leaner ecosystem and less of the big-pier social sprawl.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Choose PicoClaw</span>
          <h2>If you care about tiny hardware</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Raspberry Pi dreams, low-RAM setups, edge experiments, and speed obsessives.</li>
            <li><strong>Choose it if:</strong> small footprint matters more than broad ecosystem gravity.</li>
            <li><strong>Watch for:</strong> a more focused shoreline and less mainstream documentation weight.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
          <span class="mini">Choose NemoClaw</span>
          <h2>If safety posture is the main question</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> people exploring stronger rails, policy controls, and sandboxed operation.</li>
            <li><strong>Choose it if:</strong> your main question is “how do I run this class of thing with more guardrails?”</li>
            <li><strong>Watch for:</strong> alpha software realities, rougher edges, and official-channel dependence.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card full">
          <span class="mini">My practical answer</span>
          <h2>Default recommendations</h2>
          <p>If you want the broadest, most established route, start with <a href="https://openclaw.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenClaw</a>. If you want a more legible and security-minded starting point, try <a href="https://nanoclaw.dev/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NanoClaw</a>. If you want small hardware and low overhead, head toward <a href="https://picoclaw.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PicoClaw</a> — and treat PicoClaw Armored as a stronger-flavored branch of that route, not a totally separate harbor. If you are specifically studying safer agent operation, read deeply before experimenting with <a href="https://docs.nvidia.com/nemoclaw/latest/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NemoClaw</a>.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

